My supervisor, previous supervisor, the VP of my department, and nearly all of my coworkers are aware of my ADHD diagnosis. And everyone but my current supervisor has had 0 issue accommodating me, as the accommodations are QUITE reasonable.
I'm literally following the ADA'S guidance per their website. I've disclosed my diagnosis MANY times and have never been asked for documentation.

He's decided that writing me up for these issues without a verbal warning is going to motivate me to "fix" the issue. My psychiatric disability isn't going to be fixed by reprimand. Yknow what would solve the issue though? The reasonable recommendations I've requested many times

Healthy beliefs have to have room to evolve, change, and include others. Knowing something that cannot be proven leads way to broken hearts, black and white thinking, toxic belief systems,, and exclusionary practices, among more insidious things.

Forcing people to conform to a specific parcel of knowledge under the guise of belief is robbing them of them of the very thing you pretend to promise them. By knowing, you cannot believe, and by strictly defining that belief, you choke out anything healthy about that belief.
Belief is colorful, rather than gray, because belief cannot adhere to one color binary, because there are too many possibilities at play within a belief. A single belief contains worlds.
Just because you know it, doesn't mean it's a fact. Knowing, though, is concrete, regardless of its validity. Belief by definition cannot be concrete, because it implies that you *do not know*.

I didn't believe the sun would rise. I knew it would rise. I didn't believe Joseph Smith was a prophet. I knew it. I didn't believe in God. I knew he was there. Getting healthy for me, has meant having to rebuild everything I thought I knew.

It took years of therapy for me to understand that I could choose what I believe, and that's when I realized that I didn't believe anything at all, and rather that I had only known things my entire life
But rather that everything is colorful. Belief inherently cannot be black and white, because as soon as it is concrete, it is no longer belief, but rather something that you know.
